One hot summer day, my friends and I decided to go hiking and climb mountains. We chose a nearby mountain. At first the weather was cool, however, as we continued up the hill the sun became hotter and hotter, and the air felt hot and humid. Although we try to stay hydrated, we soon start to feel tired and low on energy due to the strenuous exercise and heat. I began to feel dizzy and have a headache, and gradually became weak. I realized it could be a sign of heat stroke. I told my friends, and they started noticing abnormalities in their bodies, too. We found a shady place to rest and kept exercise to a minimum. I felt worse and worse, I had a bad headache, and I even had symptoms of nausea and vomiting. Friends are experiencing similar symptoms. In an emergency, we immediately sought help and called the emergency number. Rescue workers arrived at the scene and provided us with first aid. They moved us to a shady spot and provided us with cooling towels and enough water to keep us hydrated. After a period of rest and medical care, our symptoms gradually eased. Rescuers advised us to regain our strength slowly and avoid exposure to the heat. Until we're completely back to normal.

One hot summer day, one of the people I met was named John. John is an elderly retiree who lives in an old-fashioned apartment with no air conditioning. One day, the temperature suddenly soared to 40 degrees Celsius, and the air was filled with heat. John got into trouble with heatstroke because he didn't take measures to prevent it in time. When I visited John that afternoon, I found him lying on the sofa, his forehead covered with sweat, his face pale, and his breath short. He told me he felt dizzy, nauseous and weak, and even had some confused thoughts. I knew right away that he might have had heat stroke. I quickly helped him find some cold water, let him slowly drink, and use a wet towel to cool his forehead. Meanwhile, I called the emergency services and asked for medical help. With the help of paramedics, John was taken to hospital for treatment

On a hot summer day, we took part in a fierce football match. Because of the hot weather, I exercised hard during the race and sweated a lot. I began to feel dizzy and weak. It's one of the classic symptoms of heat stroke. After realizing I was unwell, my teammates quickly helped me lie down and lower my temperature with a wet towel. When the emergency services arrived, they moved me to the shade and drank some electrolyte drinks to replace the electrolytes that were lost in my body. The paramedics continued to monitor my temperature and symptoms. As my temperature gradually dropped, my condition began to stabilize. The medical staff also conducted a detailed interview and examination to determine if there were any other complications.

Old neighbor, living alone in his house. On this day, the temperature in the community was unusually high, breaking through the usual limits. Neighbors noticed that there was no movement in the old man's house, and the usually lively old man did not appear. A concerned neighbor couldn't resist visiting the old man. He tapped on the old man's door, but there was no answer. Neighbors became concerned about the man's safety, and he called the police and called emergency services. When the door was forced open, the old man slumped in a rocking chair, sweat streaming down his forehead. His face was pale, he had difficulty breathing, and he had lost consciousness. Emergency workers did their best, and thermometers measuring body temperature produced alarming numbers. The old man's body temperature has reached dangerous levels, and the random breathing is worrying. Although the medical staff tried their best to save him, the old man's life was eventually lost irretrievably.

One hot summer day, I noticed my neighbor, an elderly lady, working hard in her garden. At that time, the temperature had exceeded 30 degrees Celsius and the sun was very strong. I noticed that she was pale and had sweat on her forehead, but she didn't seem to be aware of her condition. I immediately realized that she might be in danger of heat stroke, so I walked over to her and asked if she needed help. She insisted she was fine, just a little hot. However, her tone was vague and her actions became erratic. I immediately realized that this was an emergency, so I decided to take action right away. I helped her get out of the sun-soaked garden and into the shade. I offered her a glass of cold water and patted her cheek gently to help keep her awake. I called the emergency services immediately and told them about our situation. They sent an ambulance immediately. While waiting for rescuers, I continued to give her fluids and dabbed her forehead and neck with a damp towel to help lower her body temperature. After the rescuers arrived, they conducted an initial examination of her and decided to send her to the hospital for further treatment and observation. They told me she had an elevated temperature, but luckily we acted in time to avoid more serious consequences.

However, her tone was vague and her actions became erratic. I immediately realized that this was an emergency, so I decided to take action right away. I helped her get out of the sun-soaked garden and into the shade. I offered her a glass of cold water and patted her cheek gently to help keep her awake. I called the emergency services immediately and told them about our situation. They sent an ambulance immediately. While waiting for rescuers, I continued to give her fluids and dabbed her forehead and neck with a damp towel to help lower her body temperature. After the rescuers arrived, they conducted an initial examination of her and decided to send her to the hospital for further treatment and observation. They told me she had an elevated temperature, but luckily we acted in time to avoid more serious consequences.

Many residents experienced heat stroke in the hot weather. These include people vulnerable to heat, such as the elderly, children and the chronically ill. They may experience symptoms of heat stroke such as dizziness, fatigue, nausea and vomiting. In hot weather, the concentration of pollutants in the air may increase, which poses a threat to respiratory health. Residents may experience symptoms such as wheezing, coughing and difficulty breathing, especially those who already have respiratory problems. Hot weather increases the risk of cardiovascular disease. Residents may experience symptoms such as heart palpitations, chest tightness, and elevated blood pressure. For people who already have conditions such as heart disease and high blood pressure, hot weather can lead to more serious health problems. In hot weather, the human body is prone to water loss and electrolyte imbalance. Residents may experience dehydration symptoms such as thirst, headaches, weakness, and muscle cramps. Prolonged exposure to high temperatures can also lead to electrolyte imbalances, which can affect the body's normal functions.

My neighbor, an elderly gentleman, enjoys being outdoors and caring for his garden. Although I repeatedly warned him to be cautious in the face of the heat wave, he always responded with optimism and said, ""I have experienced hot summers when I was young, I will be fine."" One day I noticed him continuing to work in the garden in the heat of midday. I was concerned that he might be affected by the heat wave, so I persuaded him to go inside and rest to avoid excessive exposure to the heat. However, he said he felt fine, just a little hot. When I got home a few hours later, I noticed that he wasn't moving around the yard as usual. I went to knock on the door, but I got no response. I was so worried that I immediately called the police and asked them to deal with the critical situation. Police and emergency services quickly arrived and entered his home. However, he had lost consciousness and was having difficulty breathing. Emergency personnel immediately began administering first aid, trying to restore his breathing and heartbeat, and rushed him to the hospital. Unfortunately, he eventually died of a heat attack. This heartbreaking incident has brought great shock and sadness to the entire community.
